<section xml:id="sec-cartesian_coordinates" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Cartesian Coordinates</title>

  <introduction xml:id="cartesian_coordinates-intro">
    <p>
      In mathematics, we are interested in studying how quantities change together.
      We will restrict our attention to two quantities at a time and will often find it useful to visualize these relationships.
      The Cartesian plane is the natural setting for these visualizations.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <!-- Preview Activity -->
  <!-- <xi:include href="previews/city.ptx"/> -->

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-the_cartesian_plane">
    <title>The Cartesian Plane</title>
    <definition xml:id="def-cartesian_plane">
      <statement>
	<p>
	  The <term>Cartesian plane</term>
	  <idx>
	    <h>Cartesian Plane</h>
	  </idx>
	  is a grid system used to describe locations using two perpendicular directions.
	  The horizontal direction is usually called the <term><m>x</m>-axis</term>
	  <idx>
	    <h>Cartesian Plane</h>
	    <h><m>x</m>-axis</h>
	  </idx>
	  and the vertical direction is usually called the <term><m>y</m>-axis</term>.
	  <idx>
	    <h>Cartesian Plane</h>
	    <h><m>y</m>-axis</h>
	  </idx>
	  The plane is partitioned into four pieces called <term>quadrants</term>, depicted in <xref ref="fig-cartesian_plane"/>
	</p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <figure xml:id="fig-cartesian_plane">
      <caption>The Cartesian Plane</caption>
      <image xml:id="img-cartesian_plane">
	<latex-image xml:id="tikz-cartesian_plane">
	  <xi:include parse="text" href="tex/quadrants.tex"/>
	</latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
    
    <p>
      The type of <em>things</em> we are interested in locating will vary by application.
      In general, we will refer to these simply as <term>points</term>.
      <idx>
	<h>Cartesian Plane</h>
	<h>Point</h>
      </idx>
      A point is located in the plane by its position relative to the <m>x</m>-axis, called the <term><m>x</m>-coordinate</term>,
      <idx>
	<h>Cartesian Plane</h>
	<h>Point</h>
	<h><m>x</m>-Coordinate</h>
      </idx>
      and relative to the <m>y</m>-axis, called the <term><m>y</m>-coordinate</term>.
      <idx>
	<h>Cartesian Plane</h>
	<h>Point</h>
	<h><m>y</m>-Coordinate</h>
      </idx>
      By convention, we locate a point by first giving the <m>x</m>-coordinate, then the <m>y</m>-coordinate.
    </p>
    
    <definition xml:id="def-ordered_pair">
      <statement>
	<p>
	  An <term>ordered pair</term>, <m>(x,y)</m>, is the data of two real numbers.
	  The collection of all ordered pairs of real numbers is 
	  <me>\R^2 = \left\{(x,y) \;\middle\vert\; x,y \in \R\right\}.</me>
	</p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      We encode the position of a point using its <m>x</m>-coordinate and <m>y</m>-coordinate using an ordered pair with the <m>x</m>-coordinate first and the <m>y</m>-coordinate second.
    </p>
    
    <figure xml:id="fig-location_point">
      <caption>The <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-Coordinates of several points in the plane.</caption>
      <image xml:id="img-location_point">
	<latex-image xml:id="tikz-location_point">
